"Shibaike H., Takamiya K., Naito M.","Gasification and Combustion Behavior of Combustibles Injected into Coke Bed",2003,"Tetsu-To-Hagane/Journal of the Iron and Steel Institute of Japan","89","11",,"1093","1098",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0347537825&partnerID=40&md5=4bb4758dd3d6774ec7632c1c6597d5f2","Environ./Waterwk. Solutions Division, Nippon Steel Corp., 46-59 Nakabaru Tobata-ku, Kitakyushu 804-8505, Japan; Environ./Process Technology Center, Nippon Steel Corp., Japan","Shibaike, H., Environ./Waterwk. Solutions Division, Nippon Steel Corp., 46-59 Nakabaru Tobata-ku, Kitakyushu 804-8505, Japan; Takamiya, K., Environ./Waterwk. Solutions Division, Nippon Steel Corp., 46-59 Nakabaru Tobata-ku, Kitakyushu 804-8505, Japan; Naito, M., Environ./Process Technology Center, Nippon Steel Corp., Japan","From the viewpoint of preventing global warming and reducing maintenance costs, the reduction of coke consumption in the direct melting furnace for municipal solid waste is strongly called for. Accordingly, the authors have developed technology for injecting combustibles through the tuyeres of the direct melting furnace. This paper reports on the gasification and combustion behavior of combustibles injected into coke bed in a high-temperature combustion experiment. The main results obtained are as follows: (1) Combustibles such as plastics, combustible dust and LPG injected through tuyeres gasify and burn with priority over coke even under the combustion conditions of a direct melting furnace that has no raceway space. (2) Combustible injection through tuyeres is effective in reducing the coke consumption in the direct melting furnace.","Coke bed; Combustion; Gasification; Injection; Melting furnace; Waste","Coke beds; Combustion behavior; Coal combustion; Coal gasification; Global warming; High temperature operations; Liquefied petroleum gas; Melting furnaces; Solid wastes; Coke",,,,,,"Hirayama, N., (1999) J. Solid Liquid Wastes, 29, p. 47; Nabeshima, Y., (2000) J. Jpn. Waste Management Association, 53, p. 17; Shibaike, H., Osada, M., Takamiya, K., Naito, M., (2000) ISIJ Int., 40, p. 252; Shiraishi, M., Mori, K., Ono, H., Ishida, Y., (1994) Proc. 5th Annual Conf. of Jpn. Soc. Waste Management Experts, p. 343; Kitano, K., Tawara, Y., Ishida, Y., Ono, H., Shiraishi, M., (1996) Proc. 7th Annual Conf. of Jpn. Soc. Waste Management Experts, p. 416; Kitano, K., Murahashi, K., Shibaike, H., Tawara, Y., Ono, H., (1997) Proc. 8th Annual Conf. of Jpn. Soc. Waste Management Experts, p. 723; Yamaguchi, K., Ueno, H., Naito, M., Tamura, K., (1991) Tetsu-to-Hagané, 77, p. 1609; Shibaike, H., Osada, M., Tanaka, H., Takamiya, K., (2000) Proc. 11th Annual Conf. of Jpn. Soc. Waste Management Experts, p. 460","Shibaike, H.; Environ./Waterwk. Solutions Division, Nippon Steel Corp., 46-59 Nakabaru Tobata-ku, Kitakyushu 804-8505, Japan",,,,,,,,00211575,,TEHAA,,"Japanese","Tetsu To Hagane",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-0347537825
